There are more women than men in this sample. The women collectively have a higher income than the men. Collectively, the women have a higher spending_score than the men also.

K means clustering

Plotting the data - maybe there are 4 or 5 clusters.

mall %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = spending_score_1_100, y = annual_income_k) +
  geom_point()

Use numeric methods to determine potential number of clusters.

# scale the numeric mall data 
mall_scale <- mall %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, scale)
  1. Elbow
fviz_nbclust(mall_scale %>% 
            select(spending_score_1_100, annual_income_k), 
            FUNcluster = kmeans, 
            method = "wss", 
            nstart = 20)

Maybe 5 clusters?

  1. Silhouette
fviz_nbclust(mall_scale %>% 
            select(spending_score_1_100, annual_income_k), 
            FUNcluster = kmeans, 
            method = "silhouette", 
            nstart = 20)

Again, looks like 5 clusters.

  1. Gap Statistic
fviz_nbclust(mall_scale %>% 
            select(spending_score_1_100, annual_income_k), 
            FUNcluster = kmeans, 
            method = "gap_stat", 
            nstart = 20)
Clustering k = 1,2,..., K.max (= 10): .. done
Bootstrapping, b = 1,2,..., B (= 100)  [one "." per sample]:
.................................................. 50 
.................................................. 100

This recommends 1 cluster which isn’t correct.

Let’s go with 5 clusters.

clusterings <- kmeans(
  mall_scale %>% 
    select(spending_score_1_100, annual_income_k), 
  centers = 5, 
  nstart = 20
)
augment(clusterings, mall) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = spending_score_1_100, 
      y = annual_income_k, 
      colour = .cluster) +
  geom_point() + 
  # theme(legend.position = "") +
  labs(
    x = "spending score", 
    y = "annual income", 
    title = "Shopper clusters", 
    
  )

The clustering seems a very good fit.

Here are the mean scores for each of the numerical variables in the mall data, grouped by the cluster number.

aggregate(mall, by=list(cluster=clusterings$cluster), mean) %>% 
  select(-customer_id, -gender)

1 = older, high income, high spending 2 = older, low income, low spending 3 = younger, low income, high spending score 4 = older, high inome, low spending score 5 = middle age, high income, high spending score
